        "kelp-forest": {
            "id": "kelp-forest",
            "summary": "They enter a towering underwater forest of kelp",
            "text": "The submarine glides into what looks like an underwater forest. Giant kelp towers around them, swaying gently in the current. Some strands reach over 150 feet tall!\n\n'Kelp is one of the fastest-growing organisms on Earth,' Dr. Marina explains. 'It can grow up to two feet per day! And like trees in a regular forest, kelp creates an entire ecosystem. Hundreds of species depend on it for food and shelter.'\n\nA furry face pops up near the surface‚Äîa sea otter floating on its back!\n\n'Sea otters are a keystone species,' Dr. Marina says. 'That means the whole ecosystem depends on them. Watch what happens if I explain why.'\n\nShe pulls up a diagram. 'Otters eat sea urchins. Urchins eat kelp. Without otters, urchin populations explode and they devour the kelp forests, turning them into underwater deserts. When we protected sea otters from hunting, the kelp forests recovered‚Äîand so did all the fish, crabs, and other creatures that lived there.'",
