        "sea-turtle": {
            "id": "sea-turtle",
            "summary": "They follow a green sea turtle and learn about its incredible life",
            "text": "A graceful green sea turtle glides past the submarine. Dr. Marina follows at a respectful distance.\n\n'Green sea turtles can live over 80 years,' she explains. 'This one might be older than your grandparents! They've been swimming Earth's oceans for over 100 million years‚Äîthey saw the dinosaurs come and go.'\n\nThe turtle heads toward a patch of seagrass and begins eating.\n\n'Greens are the only sea turtles that eat plants as adults. They're actually named for the green color of their fat, which comes from all the seagrass they eat! When they graze, they keep the seagrass healthy, like underwater lawnmowers.'\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} asks, 'Where do they lay their eggs?'\n\n'On the same beach where they were born! Female turtles travel thousands of miles to return to their birth beach. Scientists think they navigate using Earth's magnetic field‚Äîlike having a built-in compass. They dig a nest in the sand, lay about 100 eggs, cover them up, and return to the sea. The babies hatch about two months later and immediately crawl to the water.'",
