        "hydrothermal-vents": {
            "id": "hydrothermal-vents",
            "summary": "They find life thriving without sunlight at volcanic vents",
            "text": "At 2,500 meters, the submarine approaches something extraordinary‚Äîblack smoke billowing from the ocean floor.\n\n'Hydrothermal vents!' Dr. Marina exclaims. 'These are cracks in Earth's crust where super-heated water, rich in minerals, shoots up from beneath the seafloor. The water can reach 400 degrees Celsius!'\n\nBut the amazing part is the life surrounding the vents. Giant tube worms, some six feet tall, sway in the current. Ghostly white crabs scuttle over rocks. Mats of bacteria cover everything.\n\n'This changes everything we thought about life,' Dr. Marina says. 'These creatures survive without any sunlight at all. Instead, bacteria use chemicals from the vents‚Äîlike hydrogen sulfide‚Äîto create energy. It's called chemosynthesis, not photosynthesis.'\n\n{{PLAYER2_NAME}}'s eyes go wide. 'So life doesn't need the sun?'\n\n'Not here! Some scientists think life on Earth might have started at places like this. And if life can exist here, maybe it exists on moons like Europa, which has a subsurface ocean and possibly volcanic vents too.'",
