        "kelp-climate": {
            "id": "kelp-climate",
            "summary": "They learn kelp forests absorb carbon dioxide",
            "text": "'Kelp forests are climate heroes,' Dr. Marina says. 'They absorb carbon dioxide from the water‚Äîand since the ocean absorbs CO2 from the air, that means kelp is fighting climate change.'\n\nShe shows them data on her tablet. 'Kelp grows so fast that it pulls in carbon at incredible rates. When old kelp sinks to the deep ocean floor, that carbon stays locked away for centuries. Some scientists call this the ocean's carbon pump.'\n\n{{PLAYER2_NAME}} looks at the towering kelp with new respect. 'So protecting kelp forests is like planting trees?'\n\n'Even better in some ways! Kelp grows much faster than trees. And there's more: kelp releases oxygen, creates habitat for thousands of species, and can even help reduce the acid in seawater caused by climate change.'\n\n'Can we grow more kelp?' {{PLAYER1_NAME}} asks.\n\n'Yes! Scientists are experimenting with kelp farms‚Äîgrowing kelp on purpose to absorb carbon and provide food. Kelp is nutritious and can be used for food, fertilizer, even biofuel. It's one of nature's superheroes.'",
