        "turtle-temperature": {
            "id": "turtle-temperature",
            "summary": "They discover warmer sand creates more female turtles",
            "text": "'Here's something amazing,' Dr. Marina says. 'For sea turtles, the temperature of the sand where eggs incubate determines whether babies are male or female!'\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} looks confused. 'Wait, not genetics?'\n\n'Nope! Cooler sand‚Äîbelow about 28 degrees Celsius‚Äîproduces males. Warmer sand produces females. And here's the problem: as climate change warms beaches, we're getting more and more female turtles. Some populations are now 99% female!'\n\n{{PLAYER2_NAME}} thinks about this. 'But they need males too, right?'\n\n'Exactly. Without males, there won't be any babies in future generations. Scientists are trying to help by creating shaded nesting areas to cool the sand, or even moving eggs to cooler locations.'\n\nShe watches the turtle glide gracefully through the water. 'Sea turtles survived the asteroid that killed the dinosaurs. They've lived through ice ages and continental drift. But they might not survive what humans are doing to their planet in just a few decades. That's why we study them‚Äîand why we need to protect them.'",
