        "reef-food-chain": {
            "id": "reef-food-chain",
            "summary": "They witness the complex food chain of the coral reef",
            "text": "Dr. Marina points out a drama unfolding before them. A parrotfish is biting chunks off the coral. A moray eel lurks in a crevice, watching. A barracuda circles above.\n\n'The reef is a theater of life and death,' she explains. 'Parrotfish are incredibly important‚Äîthey eat algae that would otherwise smother coral. They also bite off coral, digest it, and poop it out as sand. One parrotfish can produce 200 pounds of sand per year!'\n\n{{PLAYER2_NAME}} giggles. 'So beaches are fish poop?'\n\n'A lot of tropical beach sand, yes! Now watch‚Äî' The moray eel suddenly strikes, grabbing a small fish that swam too close. 'Predators keep populations in balance. Without predators, some species would multiply out of control and eat all the resources.'\n\nA shark glides silently overhead, and smaller fish scatter.\n\n'Sharks are apex predators. They've been on Earth for 450 million years, perfecting their role. Healthy reefs need healthy shark populations. When sharks disappear, the whole food chain gets disrupted.'",
